1. Introduction

Loblaws Digital wants to predict which customers are most likely to leave the platform (churn). Customer churn is expensive each lost customer means lost revenue, higher marketing costs, and lower loyalty.

Our job is to:

  • build a model that predicts churn
  • identify important customer behaviors
  • help the business make decisions to prevent churn

This notebook walks through everything:

  • Data cleaning
  • Exploratory analysis
  • Feature engineering
  • Modeling
  • Tuning
  • Deployment planning
  • Performance management
2. Assignment Objectives

Business Objectives

  • Predict customers who are likely to leave Loblaws.
  • Help the company improve customer retention.
  • Understand which factors influence churn.
  • Provide clear, actionable insights to Product Managers.

Technical Objectives

  • Perform detailed EDA
  • Build ML models (Logistic Regression, Random Forest, XGBoost)
  • Tune hyperparameters
  • Select the best model
  • Save the final model for deployment

3. Problem Definition

Goal:

Build a Machine Learning model that predicts whether a customer will churn (Yes/No).

This is a binary classification problem:

Label Meaning
1 Customer churns (leaves)
0 Customer stays

4. Stakeholders

Stakeholder What They Care About
Product Managers Which customers need retention offers
Marketing Team Who to target with discounts
Customer Service Who may need intervention
Leadership KPIs, churn rate, ROI
Data Science Team Model accuracy, fairness, reliability

5. Data Cleaning & Imputation

We fix messy or missing data so our model can learn correctly.

Steps we perform:

  1. Standardize category names

    • Example: "COD" "Cash on Delivery"
    • Example: "Phone" "Mobile Phone"

  2. Fill missing values

    • Numbers replaced with the median
    • Categories replaced with the most common value

  3. Check that no missing values remain

In[7]:
clean_df = df.copy()

# Standardize categories
clean_df['PreferredPaymentMode'] = clean_df['PreferredPaymentMode'].replace({'COD':'Cash on Delivery','CC':'Credit Card'})
clean_df['PreferedOrderCat'] = clean_df['PreferedOrderCat'].replace({'Mobile':'Mobile Phone'})
clean_df['PreferredLoginDevice'] = clean_df['PreferredLoginDevice'].replace({'Phone':'Mobile Phone'})

# Imputation
numeric_imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='median')
categorical_imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')
clean_df[numeric_cols] = numeric_imputer.fit_transform(clean_df[numeric_cols])
clean_df[categorical_cols] = categorical_imputer.fit_transform(clean_df[categorical_cols])

print("Missing Values After Imputation:")
print(clean_df.isnull().sum())
display(clean_df.head())

7. Feature Engineering

Feature engineering means creating new useful data columns
that help the model learn better patterns.

We add:

  • RecencyBucket how recently the customer ordered
  • LoyaltyScore bigger score = more loyal
  • CouponUsageRatio how often they use coupons
  • ComplaintFrequency how often they complain
  • CashbackPerOrder average cashback per order
  • HighRiskCategory customers who buy Mobile Phone often

Then we one-hot encode (convert text to numbers) the categorical features to Numeric.

In[11]:
df_fe = clean_df.copy()

df_fe['RecencyBucket'] = pd.cut(df_fe['DaySinceLastOrder'], bins=[-1,2,5,10,50],
                                labels=['Very Recent','Recent','Moderate','High'])
df_fe['LoyaltyScore'] = df_fe['Tenure']*0.5 + df_fe['OrderCount']*1.5
df_fe['CouponUsageRatio'] = df_fe['CouponUsed'] / (df_fe['OrderCount']+1)
df_fe['ComplaintFrequency'] = df_fe['Complain'] / (df_fe['NumberOfAddress']+1)
df_fe['CashbackPerOrder'] = df_fe['CashbackAmount'] / (df_fe['OrderCount']+1)
df_fe['HighRiskCategory'] = df_fe['PreferedOrderCat'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x=='Mobile Phone' else 0)

categorical_cols_fe = ['PreferredLoginDevice','PreferredPaymentMode','Gender','PreferedOrderCat',
                       'MaritalStatus','RecencyBucket','CityTier']
df_fe = pd.get_dummies(df_fe, columns=categorical_cols_fe, drop_first=True)

print("Feature engineering complete. Shape:", df_fe.shape)
display(df_fe.head())

8. Train/Test Split & Scaling

We divide the data into:

  • Training set (80%) : used to teach the model
  • Test set (20%) : used to check how well the model learned

We also scale all numeric values using StandardScaler.
This makes sure all numbers are on the same scale so the model learns better.

In[12]:
X = df_fe.drop(columns=['CustomerID','Churn'])
y = df_fe['Churn']

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y, test_size=0.2, stratify=y, random_state=42
)

scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)
print("Train/Test split and scaling complete.")

Train/Test split and scaling complete.

Insight: Stratified split ensures fair representation of churners.

# Logistic Regression
lr = LogisticRegression(class_weight='balanced', random_state=42)
lr.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
y_pred_lr = lr.predict(X_test_scaled)
y_prob_lr = lr.predict_proba(X_test_scaled)[:,1]

# Random Forest
rf = RandomForestClassifier(class_weight='balanced', n_estimators=300, random_state=42)
rf.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
y_pred_rf = rf.predict(X_test_scaled)
y_prob_rf = rf.predict_proba(X_test_scaled)[:,1]

# XGBoost
xgb = XGBClassifier(scale_pos_weight=(y_train==0).sum()/(y_train==1).sum(),
                    use_label_encoder=False, eval_metric='logloss', random_state=42)
xgb.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
y_pred_xgb = xgb.predict(X_test_scaled)
y_prob_xgb = xgb.predict_proba(X_test_scaled)[:,1]

Evaluate Models

In[14]:
def evaluate_model(y_test, y_pred, y_prob, model_name):
    print(f"--- {model_name} ---")
    print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
    print("ROC-AUC:", roc_auc_score(y_test, y_prob))
    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_prob)
    plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label=f"{model_name} ROC-AUC = {roc_auc_score(y_test, y_prob):.2f}")
    plt.plot([0,1],[0,1],'k--')
    plt.xlabel("FPR")
    plt.ylabel("TPR")
    plt.title(f"{model_name} ROC Curve")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

evaluate_model(y_test, y_pred_lr, y_prob_lr, "Logistic Regression")
evaluate_model(y_test, y_pred_rf, y_prob_rf, "Random Forest")
evaluate_model(y_test, y_pred_xgb, y_prob_xgb, "XGBoost")

10. Hyperparameter Tuning

Hyperparameters are settings for a machine learning model.

We use GridSearchCV to find the BEST settings for:

  • Random Forest
  • XGBoost

This improves accuracy and recall for churn prediction.

In[15]:
rf_params = {'n_estimators':[200,300], 'max_depth':[5,10,None], 'min_samples_split':[2,5]}
xgb_params = {'n_estimators':[200,300], 'max_depth':[3,5], 'learning_rate':[0.05,0.1]}

rf_grid = GridSearchCV(rf, rf_params, scoring='f1', cv=StratifiedKFold(5), n_jobs=-1)
rf_grid.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
best_rf = rf_grid.best_estimator_
print("Best RF Params:", rf_grid.best_params_)

xgb_grid = GridSearchCV(xgb, xgb_params, scoring='f1', cv=StratifiedKFold(5), n_jobs=-1)
xgb_grid.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
best_xgb = xgb_grid.best_estimator_
print("Best XGB Params:", xgb_grid.best_params_)

Best RF Params: {'max_depth': None, 'min_samples_split': 2, 'n_estimators': 300}
Best XGB Params: {'learning_rate': 0.1, 'max_depth': 5, 'n_estimators': 300}

Insight: Optimal parameters maximize predictive accuracy, ensuring retention efforts are directed at the right customers.The model is now improved using best-found settings.Tuning increases recall and F1 score. The best-performing model will be used for deployment.

The Random Forest will learn very detailed patterns using many trees and deep splits. Its strong but can overfit slightly.

XGBoost is boosting, meaning it learns mistakes step by step. Depth 5 and learning rate 0.1 is a good balance between accuracy and avoiding overfitting.

11. Threshold Optimization

By default, predictions use a threshold of 0.5.
But churn prediction often needs higher recall.

So we:

  1. Try many thresholds
  2. Calculate F1-score for each
  3. Pick the best threshold
In[16]:
from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_curve

probs = best_xgb.predict_proba(X_test_scaled)[:, 1]
precision, recall, thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y_test, probs)
f1 = 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall + 1e-10)
best_idx = f1.argmax()
opt_thresh = thresholds[best_idx]

print(f"Optimal threshold: {opt_thresh:.2f}, F1: {f1[best_idx]:.2f}")

y_pred_opt = (probs >= opt_thresh).astype(int)
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_opt))

Optimal threshold: 0.66, F1: 0.96
              precision    recall  f1-score   support

         0.0       0.99      0.99      0.99       936
         1.0       0.96      0.97      0.96       190

    accuracy                           0.99      1126
   macro avg       0.98      0.98      0.98      1126
weighted avg       0.99      0.99      0.99      1126

A better threshold improves recall and F1-score. Helps catch more customers likely to churn.

subgroups = ['Gender','CityTier']

        # Create mask based on the original column values in the test set
        mask = (original_X_test_data[col] == val)
        # Apply mask to y_test and X_test_scaled
        f1 = f1_score(y_test[mask], best_xgb.predict(X_test_scaled[mask]))
        print(f"{val}: {f1:.2f}")

. Observations & Recommendations Summary

Feature / Metric Observation Recommended Action Phase for Action
LoyaltyScore Low score indicates low engagement Send loyalty/reward campaigns Post-Onboarding / Early Usage
DaySinceLastOrder High value customer inactive Re-engagement emails/discounts Inactivity / Dormant Phase
CouponUsageRatio Low usage lack of incentives Targeted coupons or promotions Purchase / Engagement Phase
ComplaintFrequency High dissatisfied customer Personalized support / follow-up Anytime complaints are logged
CashbackPerOrder Low less satisfaction with incentives Optimize cashback program Purchase Phase
HighRiskCategory Certain product categories more likely to churn Extra loyalty offers / exclusive deals Product-Specific Campaigns
App Usage Metrics Low engagement likely to churn Push notifications, app tutorials Post-Onboarding / Early Usage

Key Takeaways for Action Before Customer Leaves

Continuous Monitoring: The churn prediction should run after every interaction or purchase, not just periodically.

Early Warning Indicators: Use LoyaltyScore, RecencyBucket, and ComplaintFrequency to catch high-risk customers before they churn.

Targeted Campaigns: Automated alerts in CRM for marketing/retention teams to take immediate action.

Feedback Loop: Actions (coupons, support, incentives) are logged and used to update model predictions dynamically.

Customer Lifecycle Phases & Churn Prediction Integration

Phase What Happens Where to Integrate Churn Prediction Actionable Insights / Interventions
Onboarding Customer signs up, first interactions Predict churn risk based on early behavior (app usage, first purchase, preferred categories) Send welcome campaigns, tutorials, personalized recommendations
Early Engagement / First 1-3 Orders Customer explores products and app Monitor LoyaltyScore, CouponUsageRatio, and App Engagement metrics Incentivize with coupons, loyalty points, targeted push notifications
Purchase / Active Phase Customer regularly purchases Use churn model to flag risk after each order Trigger special offers, discount bundles, cashback improvements for high-risk users
Dormant / Inactive Phase Customer hasnt purchased recently Predict churn based on DaySinceLastOrder, CashbackPerOrder, RecencyBucket Re-engagement campaigns: emails, push notifications, exclusive deals
Complaint / Dissatisfaction Phase Customer files complaints or shows low satisfaction Monitor ComplaintFrequency and SatisfactionScore in real time Personalized support calls, priority resolution, feedback loop
High-Risk Product Categories Purchase pattern in risky categories (e.g., Mobile Phone) Integrate high-risk category flag into churn prediction Exclusive retention offers, loyalty bonuses, cross-sell recommendations
